**Pre-Surgery:**
- Stop blood thinners, supplements 2 weeks before
- No alcohol for 1 week
- Arrange transportation home
- Prepare compression vest
- Plan for 1-2 weeks reduced activity

**During Surgery:**
- General or local anesthesia with sedation
- 1-3 hours depending on extent
- Outpatient (go home same day)

**Recovery Timeline:**

**Days 1-3:**
- Significant swelling and bruising
- Compression vest worn 24/7
- Pain managed with medication
- Drains may be placed (removed in days)
- Rest, no upper body movement

**Week 1:**
- Swelling peaks then decreases
- Bruising spreading but fading
- Can do desk work from home
- No lifting, reaching, driving
- Sleep elevated

**Weeks 2-4:**
- Swelling decreasing
- Can return to office work
- Light walking okay
- No chest exercises
- Compression vest still worn

**Weeks 4-6:**
- Most swelling resolved
- Light exercise okay (legs, cardio)
- No chest pressing yet
- Compression may be optional

**Months 2-3:**
- Can resume chest exercises (light)
- Most restrictions lifted
- Residual swelling still possible
- Result becoming clear

**Months 3-6:**
- Final result emerging
- Scars maturing
- Full chest training okay
- Minor swelling may persist`,
